<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Microchip Talks With U.S. Said `Constructive' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2403071994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0649 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403071994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 24 KYODO -- The just-concluded 
semiconductor trade talks between Japan and the United States 
were "constructive" in boosting the foreign share of the 
Japanese microchip market, a senior Trade Ministry official said 
Thursday. 
  Hideaki Kumano, vice minister at the Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry (MITI), was referring to an 
accord on industrial cooperation between the two countries for 
increased foreign access to the Japanese semiconductor market. 
The agreement was reached during a two-day regular meeting in 
Hawaii that ended Wednesday. 
  Japan agreed to a U.S. request for Tokyo's efforts to help 
expand use of U.S.-made microchips by Japan's automobile, 
telecommunications and game equipment sectors. 
  The Japanese Government is prepared to encourage these 
industrial sectors to step up purchases of U.S. semiconductors, 
Kumano told a press conference. But he added that does not 
represent "any government guarantee" that the foreign share of 
Japan's market will stay above the benchmark 20 percent. 
  Kumano noted that the government does not ensure any results 
on ongoing voluntary efforts within the auto industry to expand 
purchases of U.S.-made auto parts and automobiles. 
  "It is impossible for the government to ensure results 
regarding private-sector matters," he said. 
  On Japan's restraints on car exports to the U.S., Kumano 
said 
MITI has yet to decide if it will extend the practice for fiscal 
1994 starting in April. U.S. officials have said there is no 
need for Japan to continue the restraints. 

</TEXT>

