<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Says Auto Purchase Plans Cited in Package </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2403082994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0816 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403082994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 24 KYODO -- Voluntary plans by the 
Japanese auto industry on purchases of U.S. auto parts and 
automobiles will be referred to in the government's 
market-opening package to be unveiled next week, a senior trade 
ministry official said Thursday [24 March]. 
  In the package, set for release Tuesday, the government will 
probably state it "welcomes" private-sector efforts to boost 
buying of U.S.-made auto components and automobiles, said the 
official at the Ministry of International Trade and Industry. 
He declined to be named. 
  But the reference does not mean the government will 
guarantee 
results for plans by each carmaker, the official added. 
  The package will be formulated as a way to resume failed 
"framework" trade talks between Japan and the United States. 
The two countries were unable to reach accord on "objective 
criteria" as a tool to measure Japan's imports. 

</TEXT>

