<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Terada Regrets Mexican Candidate's Assassination </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2403101794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0932 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403101794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 24 KYODO -- Japan expressed regret on 
Thursday [24 March] at the assassination of a Mexican 
presidential candidate on Wednesday in Tijuana, near the U.S. 
border, during an election campaign. 
  Foreign Ministry spokesman Terusuke Terada issued a 
statement 
calling the assassination of Luis Donaldo Colosio an 
"unfortunate incident" and offered condolences. The statement 
said if the incident was an act of political terrorism, it is a 
challenge to Mexico's democracy and all the more regrettable as 
Japan has been supporting Latin American nations' efforts to 
become democratic. 
  Colosio was shot in the head and the abdomen around 5 P.M. 
shortly after finishing a campaign speech in a poor area of 
Tijuana. He died later in the evening. 
  Colosio, 44, was the candidate of the ruling Institutional 
Revolutionary Party (PRI) in presidential elections scheduled 
for August. 

</TEXT>

