<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Council Urges Telecommunications Competition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2403152794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1508 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 24 KYODO -- The Telecommunications 
Council on Thursday [24 March] advised Posts and 
Telecommunications Minister Takenori Kanzaki to take steps to 
encourage free competition among three Japanese long-distance 
telecommunications service companies. The panel gave its advice 
to Kanzaki in granting charge cut applications by Japan Telecom 
Co., DDI Corp. and Teleway Japan Corp., as the three companies 
all planned the same reduction and sought approval for their 
plans. 
  At the moment, conditions are not ripe for free competition 
among the firms because of continued quasimonopolistic control 
by Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. (NTT), the council said. 
  The three firms all proposed an average 12.3 percent cut in 
the general leased circuit charge for new medium-distance 
categories. The three companies also sought approval for an 
average 10.3 percent cut in their high-speed digital 
transmission service charges. 
  However, the council recommended to the minister that the 
proposed charge reduction plans be approved without revision. 
The rate cuts will be put into effect on April 1. 

</TEXT>

