<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry: No New Offers on Macroeconomic Steps </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2403095494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0941 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403095494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 24 KYODO -- The finance minister has 
no new offers on macroeconomic measures for Japan's trade 
package to be compiled by the end of the month, a senior 
ministry official said Thursday [24 March]. 
  "There were no specific talks on macroeconomic 
measures...and 
we can't offer something new" regarding permanent tax cuts or 
boosting public works spending, Vice Finance Minister Jiro Saito 
told a scheduled news conference. Saito was referring to an 
earlier meeting he attended at the Diet between Finance Minister 
Hirohisa Fujii and Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura. 
  The government has promised to enact tax measures by the end 
of the year. Steps envisaged include a permanent cut in income 
taxes and raising indirect levies such as the consumption tax. 
The government has also said it will consider boosting its 
10-year 430 trillion yen public works spending program if 
funding can be secured. 
  Takemura told a separate news conference that he wants to 
include "direction" of macroeconomic measures in the March 
package, but details will take until June to work out. But the 
chief government spokesman said he "fully recognizes" the 
ministry's "unchanged" cautious macroeconomic stance. 
  Saito said the meeting covered only "general discussions," 
adding, "you (reporters) shouldn't speculate." 

</TEXT>

