<H3> <TI>   Lower House Committee Agrees on 1995 Tax Cuts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2403145794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1437 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403145794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 24 KYODO -- A lower house committee on 
Thursday [24 March] approved a proposal for major tax cuts in 
1995 and beyond to follow the planned cuts for 1994. 
  Finance committee directors of the House of Representatives 
approved the proposal to add to the special income tax reduction 
bill a provision calling for further income tax cuts in 1995 and 
beyond. The proposal was made by the opposition Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP) in an amendment to the bill submitted to 
the committee earlier in the day. 
  The current bill calls for an income tax reduction only for 
1994. 
  The amendment is due for approval at a lower house plenary 
session on Friday evening. 
  The ruling coalition earlier agreed to decide on a sweeping 
tax reform plan, including additional income tax cuts, by the 
end of the year. 

</TEXT>

