<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Private Rail Unions Threaten To Strike 25 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2403134994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1331 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403134994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 24 KYODO -- Private railway unions on 
Thursday [24 March] threatened a 24-hour strike Friday affecting 
more than 22 million people if they fail to resolve their 
differences with management over demands for a wage increase. 
The companies are asking their unions to accept a benchmark 
monthly wage increase of 10,800 yen, but the unions are pushing 
for a 4 percent increase of 11,600 yen. 
  Late Thursday evening it was still unclear whether 
last-minute talks would avert a strike. 
  Bus services by nine companies and train services by 12 
companies could affect some 22,100,000 people. In the Kanto 
region centered on Tokyo they include the Tobu, Tokyu, Keisei 
railway lines and lines operated by Teito Rapid Transit 
Authority, Keio Teito, and Sagami Railway, and in the Chubu 
region centered on Nagoya, the Nagoya Railroad Union. 
  In the Kansai region centered on Osaka and Kyoto they 
include 
the Hankyu, Hanshin, Keihan, and Nankai railway lines, and in 
Kyushu the Nishi Nippon Railroad lines. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

