<H3> <TI>   Government Seeks Diplomatic Ties With India </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2403095894 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 
24 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2403095894 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Fiji says it could rejoin the Commonwealth as soon 
as early as next year. The South Pacific correspondent, Erina 
Reddan, reports that Fiji's newly elected government wants to 
rejoin the Commonwealth and reestablish diplomatic links with 
India. 
  [Begin Reddan recording] Fiji left the Commonwealth in the 
wake of two military coups in 1987 which overthrew an 
Indo-Fijian dominated government. It broke off diplomatic links 
with India in 1989 after accusing an embassy staffer of 
interfering in local politics. Now elected for a second term as 
prime minister, one-time coup leader Sitiveni Rabuka says he 
wants a new era of racial harmony between Fijians and 
Indo-Fijians. The racist constitution which guarantees Fijians' 
political dominance over Fiji Indians must be reviewed by 1997. 
The spokesperson, (Jauna Nakabua), says it could be well enough 
on the way by 1995 to satisfy the Commonwealth that it meets its 
protection of human rights principles. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

