<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hun Sen Chairs Meeting To Discuss Pailin Victory </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2303154394 Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1300 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2303154394 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1300 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Cambodian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Communique of the office of the government spokesman -- </F>
read by announcer] 
  [Text] A joint ministerial meeting was held at 0900 on the 
morning of 23 March at the Cabinet's office chaired by Samdech 
Hun Sen, second prime minister of the Royal Government of 
Cambodia [RGC]. 
  The joint ministerial meeting focused on strengthening the 
victory won by the Khmer Royal Armed Forces [KRAF] in seizing 
control of Pailin at 1800 on 19 March. The meeting also outlined 
a number of urgent principles, targets, and measures to control 
Pailin, which had been under the Khmer Rouge since the end of 
1989. The Khmer Rouge had used this area as their autonomous 
zone and center for carrying out illegal economic exploitation 
to continue the war, carrying on the massacre, and creating 
insecurity for the Cambodian people throughout the country. In 
this connection: 
  1. The meeting discussed, examined, and determing a number 
of measures to cope with the resettlement of the people who will 
settle in the Pailin area and provide them with security; 
  2. The meeting reiterated the RGC's determination to 
rearrange the Pailin area by sending the people to settle there. 
The government also plans to develop this area. 
  3. The meeting decided in principle to set up measures to 
bring back the Cambodian people who had fled the Kingdom of 
Thailand when the KRAF launched its attack to drive the Khmer 
Rouge out of Pailin. 
  4. The meeting believed that the various foreign businessmen 
and companies which formerly dealt in gems and logs with the 
Khmer Rouge would definitely stop having contacts with the Khmer 
Rouge. At the same time, the RGC solemnly declared its 
recognition of all the agreements. [sentence as heard] The 
meeting ended at 1030 in a spirit of unity and (?responsibility). 
  [Dated] Phnom Penh, 23 March 1994 

</TEXT>

