<F P=102>  SK2403110494 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 1015 GMT 24 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK2403110494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] U.S. Secretary of Defense William Perry will visit 
the ROK next month in connection with the North Korean nuclear 
issue. Also, the situation on the Korean peninsula has been 
further strained. Under these circumstances, a North Korean 
authority to the United Nations suddenly showed the position 
today that it would resume negotiations with the United States. 
As a result, changes in the North Korean attitude regarding the 
North Korean nuclear issue newly attract our attention. We have 
news from reporter Yi Chong-ok at the desk international affairs. 
  [Begin Yi recording] A relevant authority of the North 
Korean mission to the United Nations said today that North Korea 
is willing to resume negotiations -- which are suspended at 
present -- with the United States if the ROK-U.S. joint military 
exercise is suspended and if the United States confirms to North 
Korea that it will resolve the nuclear issue on the Korean 
peninsula through dialogue. 
  Japan's KYODO NEWS AGENCY reported: The North Korean 
authority expects negotiations with the United States to be 
resumed. Also, it reported that the authority said that North 
Korea would accept the additional inspections demanded by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency when the U.S.-North Korean 
high-level talks are held. 
  The news agency reported: Such remarks by the North Korean 
authority seem to show that North Korea is intending to avoid 
the strong steps, including economic sanctions, by continuing 
dialogue with the United States. 
  Also, Japan's SISA NEWS AGENCY reported that the United 
States had decided to immediately send U.S. Secretary of Defense 
Perry to the ROK and Japan on 17 April to discuss the nuclear 
issue on the Korean peninsula. [End recording] 

</TEXT>

