<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Kim's Visit to Japan Previewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2403025294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0123 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2403025294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 24 (YONHAP) -- South Korean President 
Kim Yong-sam's state visit to Japan on Thursday will spur 
bilateral military cooperation, with Defense Minister Yi 
Pyong-tae traveling to Tokyo late next month and South Korea's 
Navy calling at a Japanese port within the year, the SANKEI 
SHIMBUN reported in a Seoul-datelined story on Thursday. 
  Quoting military sources in Seoul, the Japanese newspaper 
said the two countries would shortly agree to exchange flight 
information to prevent accidents involving military planes as 
the first step of cooperation. 
  South Korea is interested in defense exchanges and 
cooperation with Japan because its plans to promote military 
links with China and Russia have not met expectations since the 
establishment of diplomatic ties under former President No 
Tae-u, it observed. 
  Influenced by President Kim's Japan policy calling for 
future-oriented relations, the South Korean military has begun 
showing a keen interest in that country, it added. 
  Defense Minister Yi was to accompany President Kim to Japan 
in late March but has decided to go late next month for in-depth 
talks with Japanese defense leaders on military cooperation, the 
report said. 
  It is highly likely that a South Korean naval fleet will 
call 
at a Japanese port this year, entailing a return call by the 
Japanese at a South Korean port, it quoted a Seoul military 
source as saying. 
  At present, the two countries conduct two military personnel 
exchange programs a year covering mutual visits by army, navy, 
air force and joint chiefs of staff personnel. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

