<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaves for Japan, PRC Visits </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2403010894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0053 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403010894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 24 KYODO -- South Korean President Kim 
Yong-sam left Seoul on Thursday [24 February] for a weeklong 
trip to Japan and China to seek support for last-ditch efforts 
to defuse the crisis over North Korea's alleged nuclear weapons 
program. 
  Kim's trip, his first state visit to the two countries since 
taking office in February 1993, was originally designed to 
strengthen South Korea's economic ties with its nearest 
neighbors. 
  Kim told reporters Tuesday he hopes his visit will serve as 
a 
turning point in resolving the nuclear crisis on the Korean 
peninsula. 
  He said besides in-depth discussion of the North Korean 
problem, bilateral economic cooperation and closer trade ties 
will top his agenda in talks with Japanese and Chinese leaders. 
  Kim is scheduled to hold talks with Japanese Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa on Thursday and Friday, and with Chinese 
President Jiang Zemin next Monday. He will return to Seoul on 
Wednesday. 
  Kim is being accompanied by his wife Son Myong-sun and three 
cabinet ministers. 
  In a departure ceremony at Seoul airport, Kim said he will 
try to obtain support from Japan and China to resolve the 
nuclear issue and also bring North Korea around to reform and 
openness. 
  "I will explain to the two leaders of Japan and China that 
preserving reconciliation and peace on the Korean peninsula is 
important to ensuring stability and prosperity in the 
Asia-Pacific region as well as in Northeast Asia," Kim said. 
  He said North Korea has created confrontation on the Korean 
peninsula by failing to allow unhindered inspections of its 
nuclear facilities and make progress in inter-Korean dialogue. 
  "While keeping the channel of dialogue open, South Korea, 
with firm security commitment of the United States, is also 
fully determined to fight against any possible provocation by 
North Korea," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

