<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Decides To Strengthen Public Security </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2403071494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0636 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2403071494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 24 (YONHAP) -- The government has 
decided to strengthen public security and its anti-crime posture 
in preparation for any emergencies that might arise while 
President Kim Yong-sam is visiting Japan and China. 
  The government held a public security-related ministers' 
meeting on Thursday and decided to tighten overall security so 
that the president can conclude his tour successfully without 
worrying about the domestic situation. 
  Prime Minister Yi Hoe-chang presided over the meeting, 
attended by nine ministers including Home Minister Choe Hyong-u, 
Justice Minister Kim Tu-hui and Communications Minister Yun 
Tong-yun. 
  The government will be on guard against possible terrorist 
attacks on public office buildings and foreign missions while 
taking steps to beef up national security. 
  It will also strive to prevent large-scale calamities 
including forest fires and traffic accidents. 
  Meanwhile, Prime Minister Yi will preside over a 
security-related ministers' meeting on Friday to check movements 
by the North Korean forces and discuss ways to ensure security 
during President Kim's absence. 

</TEXT>

