<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Reports Beef Exports to U.S. Allowed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2403115094 Seoul YONHAP in English 1103 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2403115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 24 (YONHAP) -- Exports of Korean beef 
and its products to the United States have been made possible 
beginning April 1, a Foreign Ministry official said on Thursday. 
  He said that at a Korea-U.S. trade meeting held at the 
Foreign Ministry on Wednesday, the United States agreed to 
exclude Korea from a cattle epidemic area, paving the way for 
the exports of Korean beef to the United States. 
  Also at Wednesday's meeting, the United States protested 
over 
Korea's recent discarding of a large amount of American sausages 
for the expiration of their marketing period. 
  According to the official, a U.S. delegate said it was 
unreasonable for Korea to sharply shorten sausages' tolerable 
marketing period from 90 days to 30 days and discard imported 
American sausages based thereon. 
  The United States further asked Korea to allow the imports 
of 
the heads of codfish. But, Korea said it cannot at least until 
due steps are taken to ensure the sanitary handling of codfish 
heads which are used in the United States only as a livestock 
feed material, the official said. 

</TEXT>

