<F P=100> INTER-ASIAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on PECC General Meeting </TI></H3>
<H4>   Thai Minister Promotes AFTA Role </H4>
<F P=102> BK2503090194 Bangkok Radio Thailand Network in English 0000 
GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2503090194 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok Radio Thailand Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Minister of Commerce Uthai Phimchaichon told the 
10th international general meeting of the Pacific Economic 
Cooperation Council that the setting of the ASEAN Free Trade 
Area, or AFTA, is needed to promote the current multilateral 
trade system in the region. Minister Uthai made the remarks in 
his speech to about 600 representatives from 21 countries in 
Asia and the Pacific at the conference held in Malaysia during 
22 to 24 March 1994. He said while countries in the world have 
moved since 1980 toward groupings as regional trade blocs and 
Europe has already declared its single market in 1990, the Asian 
region should consider the ASEAN Free Trade Area, or AFTA, to 
increase its efficiency to survive and take advantage of the 
ASEAN wide market. 
  He recommended that AFTA be a potential tool for trade 
promotion in the region. He said that the free trade system 
will lead the Asian region and ASEAN to the world market as well 
as to induce foreign investors to the region. 

</TEXT>

