<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry on UN Security Council Resolution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2503064794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0639 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2503064794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 25 (YONHAP) -- The U.N. Security 
Council is expected to adopt a resolution on the North Korean 
nuclear situation around the end of this month, a Foreign 
Ministry official said Friday. 
  "The five permanent members of the council are in the middle 
of actively exchanging opinions on the content and strength of 
the resolution right now. They're almost finished and the 
resolution is likely to be decided soon," the official said. 
  The content is said to be rather weak so that China will not 
exercise its veto power, the official said. 
  The key point in the resolution is the International Atomic 
Energy Agency's additional demand to inspect two sites inside 
North Korea's radiochemical laboratory, believed to be a nuclear 
reprocessing facility, that were sealed off from earlier 
monitoring. 
  "The general feeling is that adoption of the resolution 
should not be too late," he said. 

</TEXT>

