<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Market-Opening Schedule Revised for GATT </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2503020494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0130 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2503020494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 25 (YONHAP) -- South Korea will impose 
import fees on rice and 91 other farm products and specific 
duties on soybeans and 62 additional agricultural items under a 
revised country schedule on opening its farm market necessitated 
by the Uruguay Round accord. 
  Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Minister Kim Yang-pae 
told the press Thursday the government had revised its farm 
market opening schedule submitted to the General Agreement on 
Tariffs and Trade (GATT) on March 11 through bilateral 
negotiations with the United States, the European Union and 
Australia, which pressed for revisions. 
  The revised schedule is to be sent to the GATT Secretariat 
on 
Friday, he said. 
  Under the revised schedule, rice imports will be 51,307 tons 
a year, the level first set by the government. The U.S. 
Government retracted its demand for 56,000 tons. 
  The new schedule calls for exclusion of 26 items, including 
pork, chicken and raw silk, from the 118 items subject to import 
fees under the March 11 schedule. 
  Tariff rates on 385 items, 29.3 percent of the 1,312 items 
for import liberalization under the schedule, will be lowered 
and an ad valorem duty, charged as a percentage of the value of 
an item, will be applied on 1,249 items. The number of items 
upon which an ad valorem duty or a specific duty can be 
selectively applied decreased from 97 under the March 11 
schedule to 63 under the revised one. 
  In addition, tariff rates on 354 items will be lowered to 
the 
levels set under the first schedule submitted in April 1992 at 
the request of the United States and other countries. 
  Potato powder imports will be increased from 10 tons to 60 
tons a year, while the duty on ice cream powder will be lowered 
from 60 percent to 40 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

