<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK President Kim Continues Speeches, Meetings </TI></H3>
<H4>   Says PRC Unlikely To Use Veto </H4>
<F P=102> OW2503044694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0422 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2503044694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 25 KYODO -- South Korean President Kim 
Yong-sam indicated Friday he does not think China would use its 
veto power if the UN Security Council seeks to impose sanctions 
on North Korea over the prolonged nuclear inspections issue. 
  Kim told a breakfast meeting with Korean journalists 
stationed in Japan that China, in principle, does not want to 
see a nuclear-armed North Korea but it also does not want to 
choose a path that would isolate North Korea from international 
society. 
  Pyongyang's refusal to permit complete inspections of its 
nuclear facilities, suspected of being used in a secret nuclear 
weapons development program, was referred to the Security 
Council by the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) earlier 
this week. 
  Beijing, Pyongyang's lone major ally, has repeatedly said it 
opposes trade and economic sanctions against North Korea. 
  Security Council members, however, are reportedly drawing up 
a resolution without sanctions that calls upon Pyongyang to 
accept complete IAEA inspections but analysts have suggested 
that the next step would be a resolution calling for sanctions. 
  Kim is currently in Tokyo meeting Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa and will travel to China on Saturday calling for 
support in demanding North Korea be transparent with its nuclear 
program. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-7177 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas058_a_94004" </HT>


