<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK President Kim Continues Speeches, Meetings </TI></H3>
<H4>   Urges East Asian Cooperation </H4>
<F P=102> OW2503132794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1309 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2503132794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 25 KYODO -- South Korean President Kim 
Yong-sam said Friday [25 March] a nuclear-free peace will come 
true in East Asia with joint efforts and cooperation by South 
Korea and Japan. Kim referred to North Korea's suspected 
nuclear weapons program in a banquet hosted by Japanese Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  "(North Korea) has threatened peace in this region. But 
cooperation between South Korea and Japan will surely bring a 
nuclear-free peace to (the region)," he said. 
  The South Korean president, who arrived in Tokyo on Thursday 
for a three-day visit, said he expects both countries will 
overcome a transitional period through close cooperation and 
mutual trust. 
  Prior to the speech by Kim, Hosokawa said that the 
building-up of relations of trust between Japan and South Korea 
will begin with addressing the past frankly. 
  Hosokawa touched on Japan's colonial rule of the Korean 
peninsula from 1910 to 1945, saying, "studying the lessons of 
the history from now on is a way of strengthening partnership 
(between Seoul and Tokyo.)" 
  He said it is important for Japan and South Korea to 
cooperate on every field to develop and stabilize relations 
between the two nations. 
  Hosokawa said such cooperation will convince Japan and South 
Korea that they are irreplaceable partners in an international 
society. 
  Among those who attended the banquet were former Prime 
Minister Noboru Takeshita, former Foreign Minister Michio 
Watanabe and Liberal Democratic Party President Yohei Kono. 

</TEXT>

