<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Automakers Propose Trade Talks With U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2503004894 Tokyo KYODO in English 2252 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2503004894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 25 KYODO -- Japanese automakers have 
proposed resumption of their talks with American carmakers to 
help break an impasse in bilateral framework trade talks. 
  In its "action plan for international cooperation," the 
Japan 
Automobile Manufacturers Association on Thursday [24 March] also 
proposed inviting smaller parts makers in the U.S. to regular 
business negotiations between Japanese carmakers and major U.S. 
parts makers. 
  The action program was published to coincide with the 
government's planned market-opening measures to be announced 
shortly. It is apparently designed to help break the ice in the 
framework trade negotiations, which broke down in February. 
  The private-sector talks were held twice in 1992 but no 
bilateral discussions have taken place since. 
  Following the program, Japan's five biggest carmakers 
including Toyota Motor Corp. and Nissan Motor Co. will 
separately announce individual schemes for purchases of U.S 
parts. 

</TEXT>

