<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Condition Set for Imposing Tariffs on Films </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2503095594 Bangkok MATICHON in Thai 25 Mar 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> BK2503095594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok MATICHON </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Thai </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] According to a report from the Commerce Ministry, 
during the negotiations on tax reduction under the General 
Agreement of Tariffs and Trade, the United States demanded that 
Thailand reduce its tariffs imposed on cinematographic film 
imports from 10 to 2 baht per meter. However, Thailand insisted 
on the minimum rate of 5 baht per meter and would agree to 
further lower the tariffs only if the United States removes it 
from the (PWL) watchlist. 
  Regarding the U.S. call for the calculation of import tax 
based on the value of the imports, the Finance Ministry said 
that it could not give up the present calculation system, which 
is based on the condition of the imported goods. However, 
futher details of the present tax calculation system will be 
spelled out in the memorandums on trade with the United States 
and New Zealand so as to convince the two countries that their 
exports to Thailand will not be subject to high import duties, 
at least, not higher than those calculated in the U.S.-proposed 
system. 

</TEXT>

