<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Envoy to France: `Ready for Dialogue,' `War' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2503112794 Paris LIBERATION in French 25 Mar 94 p 20 </F>
<F P=103> BR2503112794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LIBERATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Romain Franklin report: "Pyongyang Ready for Dialogue... </F>
or War"] 
  [Text] Beginning today, the UN Security Council could 
consider adopting a resolution aimed at forcing the North Korean 
regime in Pyongyang to submit to inspections by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). Pak Dong-chun, the 
North Koreanrepresentative in Paris, told LIBERATION yesterday 
that his country will view the imposition of "economic or other" 
sanctions as a "declaration of war by the United States and 
those aligned with it, including France." His statements were 
confirmed by the official North Korean radio. "The situation on 
the Korean peninsula is at a very negative turning point," Pak 
Dong-chun said. He added that his country is "ready for 
dialogue, but also for all-out war, and that this is not just a 
lot of hot air." 
  South Korean President Kim Yong-sam, who began a tour of 
Japan and China yesterday to rally support from the two 
countries, warned that "there were limits" to South Korea's 
"patience." The South Korean Armed Forces were put on a state 
of alert on Wednesday. 
  The annual U.S.-South Korean military maneuvers known as 
Team 
Spirit -- the holding of which was announced yesterday by Seoul 
-- would have "catastrophic" consequences, according to Pak 
Dong-chun. "Dialogue is still possible," he explained, "but 
first the maneuvers must be canceled." The imposition of UN 
sanctions and the actual installation of 160 Patriot antimissile 
missiles which Washington decided to station in South Korea 
"could lead to North Korea's definitive withdrawal from the 
Treaty on the Nonproliferation of Nuclear Weapons [NPT]." 
Pyongyang, which ratified the treaty in January 1992, announced 
its withdrawal from the NPT in March 1993, although it suspended 
the withdrawal in June, just one day before it was to take 
effect. 
  Yesterday, Russia suggested convening an international 
conference to find "a comprehensive settlement" to the crisis. 
According to Moscow, this conference will have to bring 
together "Russia, China, the United States, Japan, North Korea, 
and South Korea, as well as representatives of the UN secretary 
general and the IAEA director general." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

