<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chip Makers Rebuff U.S. Bid for Higher Share </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2603085994 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 Mar 
94 Morning Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2603085994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At the Japan-U.S. semiconductor talks, the U.S. 
side asked that Japan boost its purchase of foreign-made 
semiconductors in three fields -- automobiles, 
telecommunications, and game machines. In response, Japanese 
automakers and other manufacturers are perplexed at the U.S. 
request. 
  "In the past, Toyota Motor Corporation and Honda Motor 
Company announced their plans to increase the share of 
foreign-made semiconductors in their purchase of semiconductors 
to 20 percent by 1993. In fact, however, this year's share of 
foreign-made semiconductors in the purchase of semiconductors by 
the entire Japanese automobile sector is expected to fall to 8 
percent" (according to an official concerned at the 
Semiconductor Industry Association). This prospect is believed 
to have prompted the U.S. side to make the request at the 
Japan-U.S. semiconductor talks. 
  The Japanese automakers are taking a different view, 
however. 
They are rebuffing the U.S. request, claiming that "the share of 
foreign-made semiconductors in our purchase of chips is supposed 
to have already reached 20 percent" (says a senior official of 
Toyota Motor Corporation). 
  Motorola, Texas Instruments, and other American chip makers 
have admitted that the purchase of foreign microchips by the 
Japanese automakers has been steadily increasing. 
  Game machine makers are responding the same way. The share 
of 
foreign chips in Nintendo Company's purchase of semiconductors 
in 1993 was 21.3 percent and the share of foreign semiconductors 
in the total purchase of chips by Sega Enterprises is said to be 
hovering around 16-23 percent. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

