<H3> <TI>   Kim Doubts DPRK Holds Nuclear Weapons </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2603004594 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 26 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2603004594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 26 Mar Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] South Korean President Kim Yong-sam met with former 
Japanese prime ministers and leaders of both ruling coalition 
parties, and the opposition Liberal Democratic Party at the 
State Guesthouse on the afternoon of 25 March. Referring to 
North Korea's suspected nuclear development during a meeting 
with former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone, the South Korean 
president said: "I think that North Korea does not have nuclear 
weapons." This is the first time the president has acknowledged 
the nonexistence of nuclear weapons in North Korea since he 
arrived in Japan. The president went on to say: "North Korea 
is eager to develop nuclear weapons, however, I intend to 
resolve the issue while closely cooperating with Japan." 

</TEXT>

