<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Yong-sam's Tokyo Visit Assessed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803104794 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 27 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2803104794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Hiroshi Yamazaki of the Political News Department] </F>
  [Text] At his speech to the Japanese Diet, ROK President 
Kim Yong-sam solemnly suggested "putting an end to the history 
of strife between Japan and South Korea." He took an 
epoch-making step toward establishing "future-oriented" 
relations between the two countries during his visit to Japan. 
  However, tension is extremely high on the Korean peninsula 
over the DPRK's (North Korea's) suspected development of nuclear 
arms. How to deal with this nuclear issue has become the focal 
issue for Japan and the ROK at the moment. The most amount of 
time was devoted to this issue during President Kim's summit 
meeting with Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. Kim was 
determined to pursue "future-oriented" bilateral relations even 
in the face of the serious problem of nuclear arms. In light of 
such a stance, Japan has to exert serious efforts toward a new 
relationship between the two countries. 
  A top Foreign Ministry official commented that the Diet 
speech "clearly attached importance to future-oriented bilateral 
relations, rather than to the nuclear issue." 
  In his Diet speech, Kim said firmly, "We have to eliminate 
completely all ill-feelings in the past. The South Korean 
people do not hesitate to set their eyes on the bright future." 
  According to a Foreign Ministry source, Japanese officials 
were very touched by President Kim's remark. They believe "this 
is a very welcome statement for Japan." However, it is also 
true that "this is the ROK president and government's position. 
We still have to see what the South Koreans think," (according 
to a top Foreign Ministry official). 
  The Japanese assessment of this visit is: "Through this 
round of talks, we feel that we have climbed one, two, or even 
three mountains in the Japan-ROK relations," (according to a 
Foreign Ministry source). Therefore, Japan, in turn, has to 
take immediate concrete measures to deal with the nuclear issue 
and bilateral problems. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-7234 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas059__a94016" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-059-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on DPRK Nuclear Situation </TI></H3>
<H4>   Editorial Views Impasse </H4>
<F P=102> OW2403144294 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 23 Mar 
94 Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2403144294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "Stop North Korea's Provocations"] </F>
  [Text] The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
decided on 21 March to submit the issue of nuclear inspections 
of the DPRK (North Korea) to the UN Security Council [UNSC]. 
Depending on how North Korea behaves, the UNSC may discuss how 
to deal with the DPRK, with the imposition of economic sanctions 
being a possibility. It will not do the DPRK and the 
international community any good if this problem deteriorates 
any further. We repeat our call on North Korea to contemplate 
the situation coolheadedly and realistically. 
  During the recent IAEA inspection tour, North Korea 
obstructed the inspection of a number of its nuclear facilities 
which are suspected of being involved in developing nuclear 
weapons. The IAEA objected to this and demanded that the DPRK 
accept inspections immediately. North Korea refused, and thus, 
IAEA decided to bring the issue to the UNSC. The UNSC is 
expected to adopt a resolution demanding the acceptance of 
nuclear inspections, and there is a strong possibility that 
economic sanctions may also be considered. 
  In response, North Korea objected strongly to these moves, 
and it has threatened to withdraw from the nuclear 
Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT). This is the second time that it 
has made such a threat, and this is the second time that the 
UNSC has taken up this question. The international community has 
been at the mercy of North Korea. As Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa told Premier Li Peng during his visit to the PRC, "the 
international community" has reached the limit of "its patience." 
  The international community is still forced to treat the 
DPRK 
with discretion because it is concerned about the military 
action that the Kim Il-song regime might take. At the stalled 
working-level meeting on the exchange of envoys between North 
and South Korea, the North even made remarks about the 
possibility of war. On the other hand, there is also a sense of 
urgency because the issue has to do with nuclear "deadly 
weapons," and it might be too late if something is not done 
right away. 
  However, it is not advisable for the international community 
to be twisted around the DPRK's finger and to panic every time 
it does something. If this happens again and again, there is 
the danger that the DPRK will always lead the international 
community by the nose. It might be necessary to take a more 
detached attitude. 
  The United States has decided to deploy Patriot antimissile 
missiles in South Korea. It is also considering resuming joint 
military exercises with the ROK. These are obviously deterrent 
measures to stop the North from making a wrong move. We also 
hope that the channels for a solution through negotiations will 
be kept open. 
  If a UNSC resolution and economic sanctions come to pass, 
North Korea's reaction will be even more defiant. However, the 
DPRK is already very isolated, and its economy is in very 
serious trouble. There is no need to rush even if economic 
sanctions are to be imposed. 
  China's leaders are not eager to take tough measures against 
North Korea. They seem to believe that progress through 
negotiations is still possible. If so, we hope that China will 
exercise its influence to bring about tangible results. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-7235 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas059__a94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-059-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on DPRK Nuclear Situation </TI></H3>
<H4>   MOFA Task Force Established </H4>
<F P=102> OW2403110694 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 24 Mar 
94 Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2403110694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] North Korea's suspected nuclear development program 
has again been referred to the UN Security Council [UNSC]. In 
this connection, a Ministry of Foreign Affairs [MOFA] source 
disclosed on 23 March that a task force has already been set up 
within MOFA to deal with economic sanctions to be imposed by the 
UNSC on North Korea and with other situations, and that the task 
force is fully prepared to consult with other government 
ministries and agencies. Commenting on the prospect of the UNSC 
adopting a resolution, the same MOFA source pointed out, "The 
UNSC will adopt a resolution urging North Korea to accept 
complete nuclear inspections by the International Atomic Energy 
Agency and will then see how North Korea responds to the 
resolution." The source also added that the possibility of the 
UNSC imposing economic sanctions on North Korea at this point is 
slim. The source indicated that if the UNSC decides to impose 
economic sanctions on North Korea, "Japan is obliged to go along 
with them as a member nation of the United Nations." As for the 
need to amend current laws and ordinances for Japan to comply 
with the economic sanctions, the source clearly said, "Each 
government ministry and agency is now closely examining ways to 
amend them." 
  The economic sanctions against North Korea may create a 
serious situation for Japan's security, and for that reason the 
task force is expected to study 1) ways to ban remittances by 
ethnic Koreans in Japan to North Korea, for these remittances 
have been strongly criticized by the United States and other 
nations; 2) the possibility of increasing reconnaissance and 
information-collecting activities by the Self-Defense Forces in 
accordance with UNSC resolutions; 3) ways to airlift about 9,000 
Japanese in South Korea back to Japan if South Korea enters an 
emergency situation. 
  The same MOFA source indicated that "it is impossible for 
the 
Japanese Government to regulate visits by ethnic Koreans in 
Japan to North Korea through which money is remitted from Japan 
to North Korea." The source, however, declined to definitely 
comment on the possibility of suspending the issuing of reentry 
visas for ethnic Koreans. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

