<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on DPRK Nuclear Situation </TI></H3>
<H4>   MOFA Prepares Response </H4>
<F P=102> OW2403131394 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 24 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2403131394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A Foreign Ministry source indicated on 23 March 
that, in connection with the DPRK's (North Korea) suspected 
development of nuclear devices, amendments to the Self-Defense 
Forces Law (to allow the use of government aircraft to rescue 
Japanese abroad) should be promptly included on the Diet's 
agenda to facilitate the rescue of around 10,000 Japanese living 
in South Korea in case of an emergency situation developing on 
the Korean peninsula. 
  This source also touched on the issue of stopping 
remittances 
to North Korea from Japan if the UN Security Council [UNSC] 
decides to impose economic sanctions. He said that while 
remittances through banks can be stopped, those passing through 
Hong Kong and other third countries can only be stopped with the 
cooperation of the governments concerned. However, regarding 
cash carried in person to North Korea from Japan: "It is 
impossible to prohibit North Korean residents in Japan from 
visiting the DPRK. We are still considering to what extent we 
can check the flow of cash when they exit the country, and 
whether or not to issue reentry visas (because human rights 
issues are involved)." 
  The Foreign Ministry source also stated that economic 
sanctions will be imposed in several stages and that in such a 
case, considerable measures can be taken under existing laws. 
  With regard to the UNSC resolution that may be adopted by 25 
March (New York time) at the earliest, this source predicted 
that "it will not touch on sanctions and will be limited to a 
call to accept unconditional inspections by the International 
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA)." He said that whether or not 
sanctions are imposed "depends on how North Korea behaves after 
the resolution is adopted." 

</TEXT>

