<H3> <TI>   SDPJ Grapples With DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<H4>   To Send Mission to PRC </H4>
<F P=102> OW2403052394 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 24 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2403052394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 24 Mar Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] The Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] on 23 
March decided to send a mission of party Diet members, led by 
Vice Chairman Issei Inoue (director general of the party's 
International Bureau), to China for three days from 1 April to 
discuss the issue of nuclear inspections in the DPRK (North 
Korea). Among the coalition parties, the SDPJ is in the unique 
position of being the only party with connections to North 
Korea, through the Workers Party of Korea [WPK], and it wants to 
probe for a "dialogue-based" way of resolving the issue in 
meetings with Chinese officials. The mission will also conduct 
advance consultations on party General Secretary Wataru Kubo's 
visit to China in May. 
  Kazou Watanabe, director of the party's General Affairs 
Bureau, and Hajime Fukada, director of its Organization Bureau, 
are other members of the mission, and they are due to meet with 
such key Chinese officials as Liu Shuzheng, head of the CPC 
International Liaison Department, and Zhu Liang, former head of 
the department. 
  When the SDPJ met, Chairman Tomiichi Murayama spoke about 
the 
tense situation over the nuclear inspection issue on 22 March, 
and emphasized the importance of dialogue, saying, "We should 
refrain from immediate economic sanctions, and should try to 
resolve the mater through dialogue." 
  At the party planning conference held the same day, the view 
emerged that "the government should continue efforts to find a 
breakthrough in the situation by resuming Japan-DRPK talks" and 
"Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's visit to China with 
sanctions against North Korea in mind is a de-facto failure." 
  Meanwhile, on 23 March, Akira Yamagishi, chairman of the 
Japanese Trade Union Confederation [Rengo], urged the SDPJ to 
make diplomatic efforts, and expressed the hope that Murayama 
"will work on North Korea -- through the WPK -- to accept 
international opinions." 
  The SDPJ is expected to confirm, at a meeting of the Central 
Executive Committee on 24 March, that it wants to work with the 
other coalition member parties to resolve the issue through 
dialogue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

