<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 26 March Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] Commenting on the issue of North Korea's suspected 
nuclear development on 25 March, a leader of the ruling Social 
Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] said: "The SDPJ plans to 
decide what it thinks about the issue early next week." In this 
way, he indicated the SDPJ will make its official view on the 
issue clear early next week. He also stressed: "The SDPJ is 
the sole Japanese political party that has maintained a 
relationship with the Workers' Party of Korea in North Korea and 
the relationship has a long history. As one of the coalition 
partners, however, the SDPJ is in the position of shoring up the 
coalition government." He also suggested the SDPJ, in its 
official view, will press North Korea to accept all nuclear 
inspections by the International Atomic Energy Agency. 

