<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Watanabe Book Calls for Two-Party System </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2203120094 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 20 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2203120094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Michio Watanabe, former deputy prime minister and 
foreign minister of the opposition Liberal Democratic Party 
[LDP], will have his book New Conservative Revolution 
published in mid-April. In the book, he puts forth his view on a 
realignment of political parties, proposing that members of the 
LDP, the Japan New Party, and Sakigake [Harbinger] with the same 
political belief form two new parties. His book is likely to 
become a sensation because his moves, including his ties with 
Ichiro Ozawa, secretary general of Shinseito [Japan Renewal 
Party], are drawing attention. 
  Commenting on the Hosokawa government, Mr. Watanabe points 
to 
its decision to scrap a plan for the national welfare tax and a 
delay in compiling the fiscal 1994 budget, and then definitely 
says: "The coalition government has no policies and is 
incompetent. Nothing can be done unless it is removed from 
power." In his book, Mr. Watanabe claims that the basic 
political belief will be shared by "politicians who seek public 
popularity" and "other politicians who attach importance to the 
public interest," and then says: "This book calls upon the 
politicians who attach importance to the public interest. I want 
to practice real politics by rallying forces who share my 
political belief and policies." 
  Mr. Watanabe has written the book based on the result of a 
five-year study meeting that has been held by Koji Kakizawa and 
Bunmei Ibuki, members of the House of Representatives and 
bureaucrats. The two legislators will be named coauthors in the 
book. On policies, the book proposes to: 1) streamline or merge 
six government ministries and agencies by pushing for 
administrative reform; 2) introduce a federal system; 3) add 100 
trillion yen to the 10-year basic plan for public investment and 
build a high-speed information network; 4) make Japan's vigorous 
international contributions by reviewing the five principles for 
Japan's participation in UN peacekeeping operations; and 5) 
shift to a single-seat constituency system. The book calls for 
a strong political leadership in Japan to deal with the 
post-Cold War economic and political situation. It shares many 
points with Ichiro Ozawa's book: Blueprint for Building a 
New Japan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

