<H3> <TI>   Ishikawa Election Aids Bid for Coalition Unity </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803045994 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 28 
Mar 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2803045994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 28 March Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] On the evening of 27 March, Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa issued a comment regarding the victory by Seiken 
Tanimoto, the ruling coalition-backed candidate, in the 
gubernatorial election in Ishikawa Prefecture. He said: "We 
plan to solidify the unity among the ruling coalition parties in 
the future and move toward establishing a reformed political 
system." 
  Hosokawa also commented on why he thought the ruling 
coalition candidate had won. 
  He said: "We have appealed to the public, stressing not only 
the problems peculiar to Ishikawa Prefecture, but also the 
significance the election holds on the people's view of whether 
or not it is proper to continue promoting the reformed politics 
of the ruling coalition parties." 
  His remarks expressed his confidence in the future unity of 
the ruling coalition parties. 

</TEXT>

