<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Political Reasons' Behind Tension </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2703125894 Bangkok THE SUNDAY POST in English 27 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> BK2703125894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok THE SUNDAY POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A member of the Pattani Provincial Islamic Committee 
has told Prime Minister Chuan Likphai that tension in the five 
southernmost provinces has been whipped up for political reasons 
with the aim of destabilising the Government. 
  Mr Nilek Sulaiman, also an executive member of the Islamic 
Committee of Thailand, said the prime minister must not be 
confused by developments in the area, which are "politically 
motivated and have political implications." 
  Mr Nilek said he met Mr Chuan by chance on board a plane on 
Friday while on his way to Pattani. 
  The Prime Minister was at the start of a three-day official 
visit to the southern most provinces. 
  Mr Nilek said he told Mr Chuan that tension and confusion in 
the area have been intentionally created. 
  Mr Nilek ruled out reports that the bombing in Hat Yai and 
bombs found on the railway track in Songkhla's Chana District 
are the work of separatists. 
  "They want to stir up more tension in the area, which no 
doubt would have direct impact on the Government," he said. 
  "More tension will be created in the near future." Mr Nilek, 
whose sister is married to Deputy Interior Minister Den Tomina, 
said he thought tension in the area had been created by a group 
of people who want to oust Minister Den. 
  "He has so many enemies in the area and as long as he 
remains 
in his post, tension will be whipped up to discredit him and the 
interior minister," he said. 
  Mr Nilek said the Pattani municipality of which he is a 
member has been put on full alert. 
  "We can't know when they will create more trouble in the 
municipal area," he said. 
  The Muslim deputy rector of Islamic Studies at Prince of 
Songkhla University (Pattani campus), Mr Worawit Balu shared Mr 
Nilek's view. 
  Mr Worawit said he tended to believe that political motives 
lay behind the area's tensions in the past month. 
  "I'm quite sure more trouble will be created in the area," 
he 
said. 
  Many Muslim officials in the region do not believe that 
separatists are directly responsible for tension created in Hat 
Yai, he said. 
  "It may be part of a plot to destabilise the Government. 
Without doubt, tension in the area is aimed at discrediting Gen 
Chawalit and Mr Den," he said. 
  Fourth Army commander Lt-Gen Kitti Rattanachaya yesterday 
briefed Prime Minister Chuan Likphai for 30 minutes on 
counter-terrorism activities in the southernmost provinces. 
Lt-Gen Kitti spoke of the peace talks with key members of 
separatist movements in recent months. A source said Lt-Gen 
Kitti complained of the red tape which prevents local officials 
from taking prompt action when trouble occurs. The efficiency 
of intelligence gathering among government officials was 
discussed. 
  Mr Chuan later told reporters in Pattani that only a small 
group of people are involved in attempts to create trouble in 
the area. He said the situation in the southernmost region is 
not as bad as the press makes out. He has urged local people to 
help the Government tackle the area's problems. 
  Despite the peace talks, anti-terrorist operations will have 
to continue, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-7255 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas059_m_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-059 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  27 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chuan Discusses Refugee Problem, UN Help </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2703132594 Bangkok Radio Thailand Network in Thai 1200 GMT 
27 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2703132594 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok Radio Thailand Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Thai </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Speaking to reporters at Bangkok airport this 
afternoon on his return from an inspection tour of the south, 
Prime Minister Chuan Likphai said the repatriation of Cambodian 
refugees could be made after the situation in that country 
returns to normal. The prime minister said: 
  [Begin recording] [Chuan] As a matter of fact, we can bar 
them from entering our country. We must look after them for 
humanitarian reasons. Those carrying arms must be disarmed 
before their entry. 
  [Unidentified reporter] After the situation is safe, do we 
simply send them back? 
  [Chuan] This means allowing them tp cross the border into 
their country. We will not put them on buses and send them home 
because they came here without an invitation. 
  [Unidentified reporter] [Words indistinct] 
  [Chuan] These Cambodians are not permanent refugees. If the 
problem drags on, however, we should coordinate with the UNHCR 
[United Nations High Commission for Refugees] because we might 
be accused of supporting the Khmer Rouge. It is better to have 
outsiders come here to see the problem themselves. The problem 
is not that bad at this point. The refugees will not remain 
here for a long period of time. After the situation is safe, 
they must go. 
  [Reporter] It appears that the Cambodian Government is 
rather 
unhappy with the sudden repatriation of refugees without being 
contacted. The refugees reportedly returned to the areas under 
Khmer Rouge control. 
  [Chuan] We have no right to tell them where to resettle. 
They came here themselves. They have the right to go where 
they want. They are not permanent refugees. If that were the 
case, they would have been taken care of by international 
agencies from the very beginning. If they are going to be here 
for a long time, however, we will have to seek help from 
international organizations. The presence of Cambodian refugees 
has already caused a financial burden to the agencies involved. 
I heard complaints about this last Tuesday. 
  [Reporter] [Words indistinct] 
  [Chuan] The food supplies they carried with them will last 
only a short time. We will have to feed them later. 
  [Reporter] [Wordsindistinct] 
  [Chuan] They can choose where they want to stay after 
crossing the border. We will not force them to leave. 
  [Reporter] If the UNHCR asks Thailand to keep the refugees 
for an unspecified period, will we... 
  [Chuan, interrupting] We must decide if this is necessary or 
not. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

