<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Considers Sending More Men to Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2603084794 Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES in English 23 
Mar 94 p 8 </F>

<F P=103> BK2603084794 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur NEW STRAITS TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Butterworth, Tues. [22 March] -- Malaysia will 
consider sending additional soldiers to join the United Nations 
Protection Force (Unprofor) in Bosnia-Herzegovina if requested 
to do so by the UN, Armed Forces chief Jen [General] Tan Sri 
Borhan Ahmad said today. 
  However, he said, there had been no proposal yet to despatch 
extra peacekeepers to the war-ravaged country. 
  So far, Malaysia's contribution in Unprofor was sufficient 
alongside the participation of soldiers from several other 
countries, he added. 
  He told this to reporters after launching the 13th Air 
Thamal 
(Thai-Malaysia) joint exercise between the Malaysian and Thai 
air forces at the Royal Malaysian Air Force (RMAF) base here. 
Malaysia has sent about 1,500 soldiers to join the UN 
peacekeeping force in response to the atrocities committed by 
Serbs on Muslims in Bosnia. 
  Ten RMAF aircraft, including five F-5E jets and three OV-10 
reconnaissance planes, are taking part in the exercise, an 
annual series held on rotation between the two countries to 
strengthen cooperation in operational procedures. 

</TEXT>

