<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   MORNING NEWS Editor Released on Bail </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2503131294 Hong Kong AFP in English 1245 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK2503131294 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Phnom Penh, March 25 (AFP) -- Nguon Non, the founder 
and political editor of the biweekly Morning News was released 
on bail Friday after two days under arrest, he said here. 
  Ngoun Non, who was charged with libel after publishing 
several articles alleging official corruption, was a senior 
official in the cabinet of co-prime minister Prince Norodom 
Ranariddh until he founded his newspaper at the beginning of 
this month. 
  He was the first journalist to be arrested since last year's 
departure of the United Nations Transitional Authority in 
Cambodia. 
  He had been arrested while at the offices of his newspaper, 
one of the most widely read in Cambodia with a circulation of 
30,000, for failing to respond to two separate court summons. 
  The arrest came shortly after an assurance by King Norodom 
Sihanouk that freedom of the press should be guaranteed in 
Cambodia. 
  A new press law is being prepared by the government. 

</TEXT>

