<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK's Kim, Delegation Conclude Meetings, Visit </TI></H3>
<H4>   Economic Cooperation Proposed </H4>
<F P=102> OW2503053394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0511 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2503053394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 25 KYODO -- South Korean President Kim 
Yong-sam on Friday [25 March] urged more investment in South 
Korea by Japanese firms and vowed to deal with the current trade 
imbalance by actively seeking to expand exports. Kim, at the 
midpoint of his three-day visit to Japan, told Japanese business 
leaders at a luncheon, "though we are greatly concerned about 
the bilateral trade imbalance, we will endeavor to resolve it 
through the positive approach of expanding our exports, rather 
than through the passive approach of restricting imports." 
  Kim is on a weeklong tour of Japan and China to encourage 
east Asian economic cooperation as well as a coordinated effort 
to persuade North Korea to desist with its nuclear brinkmanship. 
The South Korean president sees the hard-line communist 
government of Kim Il-song as not only a military and political 
threat but also "a major impediment to regional exchanges and 
cooperation." 
  Kim sees Asia as "the most dynamic economic region of the 
world" which is "expected to emerge as the main axis for the 
global economy" in future. "We must strive to eliminate any 
obstacle to free trade and economic cooperation so as to promote 
coexistence, shared prosperity and balanced development 
throughout Asia," he said. 
  Expanding upon his November summit with Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa, Kim was optimistic about the two young 
administrations in Seoul and Tokyo. 
  "We have been able to diminish differences between Seoul and 
Tokyo over how to redress our trade imbalance and how to promote 
technological cooperation," Kim said. With regard to the trade 
imbalance that reached 8.45 billion dollars in Japan's favor in 
1993, Kim vowed, "we will work harder to improve product quality 
and reliability and meticulously fulfill delivery and other 
contract terms." 
  Kim was also optimistic that the new initiative for an 
economic partnership, scheduled to hold its first meeting in 
Seoul next month, would serve as "a major vehicle for bilateral 
dialogue and cooperation. 
  Calling his visit to Tokyo a "new catalyst for consolidating 
our forward looking bilateral ties and economic cooperation," 
Kim urged the Japanese business leaders to "actively take 
advantage of the improving investment climate in (South) Korea." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

