<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   DSP Vows To Push for Permanent UNSC Seat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803094494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0924 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2803094494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 28 KYODO -- The Democratic Socialist 
Party (DSP), one of the seven ruling parties, Monday [28 March] 
pledged to work toward gaining for Japan a permanent seat on the 
U.N. Security Council (UNSC). In its political platform for 
fiscal 1994, the DSP declared it would push for permanent 
membership in the 15-member council as well as give its 
wholehearted support to U.N. operations, including peacekeeping 
activities. 
  The DSP also called for amendments in the Self-Defense 
Forces 
Law to institutionalize the SDF's contributions to U.N. 
peacekeeping operations as its main or sub-main task. The 
platform will be formalized at a party convention in April, 
party officials said. 

</TEXT>

