<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Abolition of Special Refugee Treatment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2503134194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1314 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2503134194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 25 KYODO -- A quarter of the 13,768 
Indochinese "boat people" who reached Japan between 1975 and 
March this year are Vietnamese who settled permanently under a 
screening system abolished this month, the Justice Ministry said 
Friday [25 March]. Japan did away with its special treatment of 
Indochinese refugees on March 4 in line with an international 
agreement on the screening system. 
  Vietnamese boat people arriving in Japan in the future will 
receive the same treatment as any other arrival. 
  Of the 13,768 boat people who landed since May 1975, when 
Vietnamese refugees first arrived, 3,416 are Vietnamese who 
opted for permanent settlement, officials said. The ministry 
said that in the same period 3,498 Chinese nationals posing as 
Vietnamese refugees also arrived in Japan, although their 
numbers have fallen off in recent years. 
  Other Vietnamese have gone to third countries to settle and 
those posing as refugees have been forcibly repatriated. 
  A June 1989 international conference on Indochinese refugees 
adopted the set of special screening measures to determine 
whether they qualified for refugee status. But with subsequent 
changes in Vietnam, a conference in February elected to revise 
the measures, and Japan's cabinet gave its approval to abandon 
them as of March 4. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-7292 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas059_a_94021" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-059 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Air Route From Hakodate to Sakhalin Agreed </TI></H3>
