<H3> <TI>   Major Banks To Give Long-Term Loans to China </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2703040194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0251 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2703040194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 27 KYODO -- Japan's major commercial 
banks will provide full-scale long-term loans for China in 
collaboration with international lending organizations to 
develop the country's infrastructures such as power stations and 
petrochemical facilities, the NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN said Sunday. 
  Local affiliates in Hong Kong of six major banks -- Fuji 
Bank, Sanwa Bank, the Bank of Tokyo, Sumitomo Bank, Mitsui Trust 
and Banking Co., the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan -- will take 
part in April in a 380 million dollar joint financing led by the 
Asian Development Bank to the People's Bank of China as key 
members, the business daily said. 
  The six Japanese banks and other foreign commercial banks 
will provide a total of 78 million dollars in cofinancing with 
the 15- year loan. The loan will carry an interest rate of that 
of libor, or London interbank offered rate, plus 0.7 percent, 
the NIHON KEIZAI said. 
  The Bank of Tokyo has also decided to participate in 15-year 
joint loans totaling 470 million dollars initiated by the World 
Bank to the Chinese Government as a key managing bank, according 
to the paper. 

</TEXT>

