<H3> <TI>   PRC To Join Oil Project in Papua-New Guinea </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803123294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1155 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2803123294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 28 KYODO -- China, facing rapidly 
growing domestic demand for crude oil, has joined a Japanese 
trading house in developing oil in Papua New Guinea, officials 
of the Japanese partner said Monday [29 March]. The officials 
of Marubeni Corp. said the project brings together the Japanese 
firm and two Chinese state-run enterprises, China National 
Petroleum and Natural Gas Corp. and China International Trust 
and Investment Corp. 
  Under the present plan, the three partners will engage in 
oil 
development in a concession to be acquired in the central part 
of Papua New Guinea to start commercial production within a few 
years, they said. 
  China became an oil-importing nation last year due to strong 
demand for crude oil resulting from high-paced economic growth. 
  The officials said full-scale production at the oil-rich 
Tarim Basin in northwestern China will not start in the current 
century. 
  In the oil development in Papua New Guinea, they said 
sharing 
of investment estimated at 100 billion yen will be decided later. 
  Most of the oil produced at the concession will be brought 
to 
China for domestic consumption but some of it will be sold 
overseas to earn foreign currency, they said. 

</TEXT>

