<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Addresses ARH Working Group Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803060494 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 0309 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2803060494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video; from the "NHK News" </F>
program] 
  [Text] Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa addressed today's 
inaugural meeting of the Administrative Reform Headquarter's 
[ARH] working group to promote imports and said Japan was 
expected to build an open economy and society. Among other 
things, the prime minister stressed the need for deregulation to 
close the commodity price gap between home and abroad. 
  With plans to finalize its voluntary market-opening package 
in late June, the government has now set up within the ARH a 
working group to promote imports, following the earlier 
establishment of a working group to study deregulation in the 
housing and land sectors. 
  At the working group's inaugural meeting held this morning, 
Prime Minister Hosokawa said no one needed to study everything 
that went on during the Japan-U.S. framework trade talks to 
realize Japan was expected to build an open economy and society. 
Promotion of this effort would lead to the correction of and 
reduction in the commodity price gap between home and abroad, he 
added. 
  A specialist from the private sector, who is also a member 
of 
the working group, suggested at today's meeting that to correct 
the price gap Japan should ease regulations which are tighter 
than in most other countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

