<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Urges Deregulation, Openness </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803061294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0520 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2803061294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 28 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa on Monday [28 March] called for greater economic 
openness, noting that the Japan-U.S. economic framework talks 
are evidence of increasing calls for Japan to liberalize its 
market. Speaking at a working group meeting on steps to boost 
imports and improve market access, the third such meeting to be 
held under the administrative reform promotion headquarters led 
by the premier, Hosokawa said, "we need to establish an 
economically open society." 
  "Our efforts should contribute to shrinking the differences 
in prices in Japan and abroad," he added, calling for active 
discussion of ways to rectify price differentials. 
  Previous meetings focused on housing and real estate issues, 
and also conferred on information and telecommunications. 
  The Japanese Government is planning to draw up 
market-liberalizing measures based on the discussions of the 
three working groups by late June, ahead of July's Group of 
Seven (G-7) summit. 
  At the working group meeting, Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata 
said "drastic measures, not abstract ones," should be 
implemented. 
  Experts from the private sector said that regulations should 
be revised to be more in line with international standards. 

</TEXT>

