<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo `Action Plan' for Market Opening Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2603065094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0644 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2603065094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 26 KYODO -- The government will unveil 
an "action plan" next week to help foreign companies participate 
more fully in Japanese markets, government sources said Saturday 
[26 March]. The plan will include tax incentives, low-interest 
loans and support in establishing welfare facilities for foreign 
companies operating in Japan. 
  In order to encourage foreign companies to export more to 
Japan or to make more investment in the country, the plan will 
also call for enhancing information provided by Japanese 
organizations. For example, it will call on the Japan External 
Trade Organization (JETRO), which long pushed Japanese exports 
but has recently begun promoting imports, to send its experts on 
trade and investment to 12 cities overseas such as San Francisco 
and Milan. 
  The action plan will be unveiled as part of a new 
market-opening package the government is expected to announce 
Tuesday, the sources said. They said the government will review 
the action plan every year to show its trade partners its 
continued efforts on the matter. 
  The plan for fiscal 1994, starting from April 1, will be in 
line with the government's budget plan, they said. 
  Another feature of the action plan will allow foreign 
companies to carry over losses incurred within the initial three 
years of operation in Japan for a period of 10 years, rather 
than the current limit of carrying losses for seven years, they 
said. 
  The government will also ease within the year conditions for 
providing a government-guarantee of debt for foreign companies, 
so as to make it easier for them to raise capital, the sources 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

