<H3> <TI>   Appliance Discount Shop Asked Not To Sell Rice </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2503122094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1159 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2503122094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 25 KYODO -- The Food Agency has asked 
an electric appliance discount store operator to scrap its plan 
to sell rice, the company reported Friday [25 March]. 
  Jonan Denki Co., which operates a discount store chain in 
the 
Tokyo area, said it plans to sell 29 tons of a popular domestic 
rice brand harvested in Akita Prefecture, starting on Sunday. 
The company said the agency asked it to call off the plan, 
warning that selling rice without a government license will 
constitute a violation of the Domestic Food Control Law. 
  Toshio Miyaji, president of the company, told reporters he 
has no intention of changing the plan at present. 

</TEXT>

