<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tanabe Gives Opinion on Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803093294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0857 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2803093294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 28 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa may be forced to quit if the Diet remains deadlocked, 
according to a former chairman of the Social Democratic Party 
(SDP), the largest force in the seven-party ruling coalition. 
  "If the (opposition) Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) 
persistently refuses to open (Diet) deliberations, there would 
be only two options -- whether only the ruling parties 
deliberate as an extraordinary measure or Hosokawa takes 
responsibility (for the delay)," Makoto Tanabe said in an 
address in Tokyo. The LDP has refused for more than two weeks 
to start deliberations on the fiscal 1994 budget, already two 
months behind schedule, until Hosokawa gives a full accounting 
of a 100 million yen loan he received from the scandal-ridden 
Sagawa Kyubin trucking business group. 
  In past Diet sessions, Hosokawa has repeatedly said he took 
the loan to help finance repairs on his residence in Kumamoto 
Prefecture and later repaid it to Sagawa Kyubin's network of 
trucking and parcel-delivery companies. 
  Tanabe also said Hosokawa should not dissolve the House of 
Representatives. He said he should not call an election under 
the current system. 
  The Diet recently passed a package on changing the election 
system, but the bills have not yet taken effect. 

</TEXT>

