<H3> <TI>   Komeito Stresses Policy Accord Among Parties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2503123594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1057 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2503123594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 25 KYODO -- Common policies will be a 
major precondition for parties to promote electoral cooperation 
and aim at victory in the next general election for the House of 
Representatives, a key figure in the ruling coalition said 
Friday [25 March]. 
  Yuichi Ichikawa, secretary general of Komeito, one of the 
seven coalition parties, told a press conference that common 
defense and energy policies are particularly important. 
  Ichikawa's remark alluded to policy differences between the 
Buddhist-backed Komeito and the largest party in the coalition, 
the Social Democratic Party (SDP), which has long been opposed 
to the Self-Defense Forces [SDF] and nuclear power plants. 
  Ichikawa, who along with Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] 
Secretary General Ichiro Ozawa, is viewed as a key coalition 
strategist, urged the SDP to break away from its longstanding 
basic stance that the SDF is unconstitutional and that Japan 
should promote development of safer energy sources as a 
substitute for nuclear power stations. 

</TEXT>

