<H3> <TI>   Kono Criticizes Hosokawa for Policy Failures </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803060694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0517 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2803060694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 28 KYODO -- Liberal Democratic Party 
(LDP) President Yohei Kono on Monday [28 March] slammed the 
government of Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa for its perceived 
failure to tackle a number of pressing political tasks. 
Speaking at a lecture, Kono pointedly criticized Hosokawa's 
abortive tax hike plan that would have replaced the current 3 
percent consumption tax. 
  Stating that the Hosokawa administration has raised doubts 
about its political capability since its formation last summer, 
the LDP chief also said the government should be blamed for the 
long delay in the Diet debate on the fiscal 1994 state budget. 
The delay is due largely to the government's decision to 
postpone customary year-end budget formulation until early this 
year, Kono said. 
  Kono also demanded that Hosokawa come clean on a 
questionable 
loan he allegedly received from a scandal-tainted trucking firm. 
  Kono is the first LDP president who has failed to become 
prime minister in nearly four decades. Under the LDP rule that 
ended last August, the post of party chief automatically carried 
the premiership because of the party's majority strength in 
parliament. 

</TEXT>

