<H3> <TI>   Hashimoto Predicts Lower House Dissolution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2503045194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0424 GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2503045194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kanazawa, March 25 KYODO -- Former Finance Minister 
Ryutaro Hashimoto predicted Friday [25 March] that a row over 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's alleged role in a money 
scandal will lead to dissolution of the House of Representatives 
and a general election. Hashimoto, chairman of the Policy 
Affairs Research Council of the opposition Liberal Democratic 
Party (LDP), said the row over the alleged scandal is 
threatening the passage of the fiscal 1994 budget program. 
  Diet business has been stalled, leaving the 73.08 trillion 
bugdet in limbo, by the LDP's demands that Hosokawa release more 
data about a loan he says he received from Sagawa Kyubin Co. in 
1982. The LDP says it will continue to refuse to open budget 
deliberations until Hosokawa meets its request. 

