<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Recession `Discouraged' Building of New Plants </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803124794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1043 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2803124794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 28 KYODO -- Japan's prolonged 
recession apparently discouraged manufacturers from building new 
production facilities in 1993, with construction of new 
factories decreasing for the fourth straight year, a government 
report said Monday [29 March]. 
  The Ministry of International Trade and Industry said 
corporate acquisitions of land for new factories in 1993 
decreased 33.8 percent from the year before to 1,634 cases, the 
lowest since 1979. 
  The total tract of land acquired for new plants also dropped 
28.7 percent to 2,290 hectares, the ministry said. 
  The ministry said the report was based on a survey of 
corporate purchases of land for new factories, covering 1,000 
square meters or more. 
  Citing another survey conducted last fall on capital 
investment plans, the ministry predicted the sluggish trend will 
continue in 1994. 
  The ministry said land acquisitions decreased in most 
regions 
covered in the survey. 

</TEXT>

