<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Household Spending Reportedly Grows in Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803064494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0607 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2803064494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 28 KYODO -- Japan's household spending 
in January stood at 328,431 yen, an inflation-adjusted increase 
of 2.7 percent from a year earlier, posting the fourth straight 
year-on-year rise, the government reported Monday [28 March]. 
In nominal terms, the yearly growth rate stood at 3.8 percent, 
the Management and Coordination Agency said. 
  The agency said spending by salaried workers' households 
grew 
a net 0.6 percent for the first upturn in nine months. Spending 
by households of nonwage earners such as the self-employed 
surged 6.0 percent in real terms, the agency said. 
  Overall, household expenditures on education and housing 
climbed 16.9 percent and 14.2 percent, respectively, over a year 
earlier while those on transportation and communication, 
furniture and household goods, and utility rates gained 7.7 
percent, 5.8 percent and 5.3 percent, the agency said. 
  Spending on medical care declined a net 3.0 percent, the 
agency said. 
  It said expenditures on food accounted for 72,458 yen, up 
1.6 
percent in nominal terms but down 0.5 percent in real terms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

