<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry To Promote Telecommunications in Cities </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2603110694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1029 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2603110694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 26 KYODO -- A ministry study panel 
will call for improving the telecommunications network systems 
of 288 local prefectures, cities and villages, ministry 
officials said Saturday [25 March]. 
  The study body, attached to the Ministry of Posts and 
Telecommunications, will file an interim report later this month 
calling for a redesign of the local networks under the "Neo 
Teletopia Project." 
  Under an upgraded version of the 1983 "Teletopia Project," 
all local areas will eventually be integrated into a nationwide 
network. 
  The Telecommunications Council, an advisory panel to the 
posts minister, has discussed the development of an optical 
fiber information network, officials said. 
  The Neo Teletopia Project is preparing for Japan's next- 
generation telecommunications network in the age of multimedia, 
which will require vast data-processing resources. 
  Under the current Teletopia Project, local governments 
receive financial aid to improve their telecommunications 
systems if deemed necessary. So far, Okinawa Prefecture and 287 
cities, villages, wards and towns have received such support 
from the central government. 

</TEXT>

