<H3> <TI>   SRV Official: U.S. `Triggered Tension' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2603052994 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0408 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2603052994 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, March 26 (KCNA) -- Vietnam and Malaysia 
on March 24 conferred on mounting tension in the Korean 
peninsula and called on the international community to help 
avert any possible outbreak of war, according to a foreign press 
report from Kuala Lumpur. 
  The two countries shared this view during talks between 
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamed and General Secretary 
of the C.C. [Central Committee], the Communist Party of Vietnam 
Do Muoi, an aide to Do Muoi said. 
  The aide said that the U.S. military reinforcement in South 
Korea was "unwarranted and an act of provocation against the 
North", adding: "This spectacular military display by Washington 
against Pyongyang must be taken seriously." 
  The aide contended that Washington had triggered tensions in 
the Korean peninsula in the hope of diverting world attention 
away from growing U.S. domestic problems, President Bill 
Clinton's fate in the "Whitewater scandal" and other issues. 

</TEXT>

