<H3> <TI>   U.S. Threat to Nonnuclear States Denounced </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2703081694 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0802 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2703081694 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Nuclear Hysterics"--KCNA headline] </F>
  [Text] Pyongyang, March 27 (KCNA) -- The U.S. Defense 
Department in an annual report recently submitted to the 
President and Congress suggested that in case non-nuclear states 
developed and used chemical or biological weapons, they should 
"be restrained with the use of nuclear weapons." The hardliners 
argue that this measure would be "an effective means of curbing 
the development of chemical and biological weapons by 
non-nuclear states". 
  This openly revealed their intention to threaten all the 
non-nuclear states with nuclear weapons and monopolize chemical, 
biological and nuclear weapons, stresses NODONG SINMUN today. 
  The news analyst says: 
  If this ambition of the United States is overlooked, the 
non-nuclear states cannot be free from U.S. threat of nuclear, 
chemical and biological weapons. 
  The demand of the hardliners of the U.S. military for the 
"use of nuclear weapons" is patent proof of the falsehood of 
U.S. propaganda that it "is a peaceful state obliged to prevent 
nuclear proliferation worldwide." 
  If the U.S. is really interested in promoting a fair 
implementation of the nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty [NPT], it 
must assure the international community it will not threaten the 
non-nuclear states with nuclear weapons and show its will for 
nuclear disarmament in practice. 
  The U.S. nuclear threat to non-nuclear states increases the 
partiality of the NPT, which imposes unilateral restriction and 
inspection on non-nuclear states while recognizing the right of 
nuclear monopoly of the nuclear-weapon states. 
  In abusing the NPT, the United States seeks to monopolize 
the 
nuclear weapons and, by wielding them at random, lord it over as 
the dominator of the world twisting all countries round its 
finger. 
  Nuclear threat cannot be a cure-all. 

</TEXT>

