<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Australia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Announces Cabinet Reshuffle 25 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2503083194 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 
25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2503083194 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Australia's Prime Minister Paul Keating has 
elevated a junior left-wing minister to cabinet as well as 
giving Dr. Carmen Laurence the rapid promotion expected in his 
latest ministerial changes. In a wider than anticipated 
reshuffle, science has had a major elevation into cabinet, and 
Linda Mottram reports the deputy prime minister, Brian Howe, has 
defied his critics to take on a significant new area. 
  [Begin Mottram recording] Carmen Laurence, picked as a 
future labor leader, is in cabinet as health and human services 
minister less than a week after taking up her new seat in 
federal parliament. A second edition to the front bench is 
Queensland's right-winger, Con Sciacca, becoming veteran affairs 
minister. A third is former minister, Gary Punch, taking on 
defense, science, and personnel. Rewarded is left-winger, John 
Faulkner, who is elevated to cabinet as environment minister; 
another left-winger, the deputy prime minister, Brian Howe, as 
regional development to his housing responsibility. Chris 
Schacht moves to troubled science arm of his small business and 
customs portfolio. Science is elevated to cabinet under 
Industry Minister Peter Cook. Other changes cover 
administrative services, special ministerial state, and some 
parliamentary secretaries. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

