<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Australia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Macedonian Council Calls Strike </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2803031094 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0100 GMT 
28 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2803031094 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Macedonian Council of Australia has called for a 
nationwide campaign of civil disobedience against the federal 
government's use of the term Slav Macedonians. The term refers 
to members of the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia. 
  The council has called on Australia's 200,000 Macedonians to 
oppose the federal government's move. The council wants members 
filling out official forms to use only the term Macedonia when 
describing their country of birth and for appeals to be lodged 
if government agencies failed to recognize the term. 
  South Australia's spokesman for the Macedonian Council, 
Alexander Glevchev, admits the campaign may force hardship upon 
members of the community. 
  [Begin Glevchev recording] Hardship is a relative term when 
you are a Macedonian person. We came out here many years ago -- 
our people escaping prosecution, starvation, and war. This 
hardship could be minor in relevance to that. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

