<H3> <TI>   Unification Minister on DPRK Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2703105794 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 1010 GMT 27 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK2703105794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yi Yong-tok, deputy prime minister and minister of 
the National Unification Board, said that he hopes that the 
North Korean nuclear problem be peacefully resolved through 
dialogue before the sanctions are imposed by the United Nations. 
However, if North Korea does not show any change in its attitude 
to the last and sanctions are inevitable, the government will 
work out all possible measures based on the international 
cooperation system. 
  Deputy Prime Minister Yi stressed this while appearing in 
the 
program, "Diagnosis of Policies" carried by KBS-1 television 
network. He said that although North Korea did not show any 
indication of military provocation, it intensified slander, 
propaganda, and instigation activities against South Korea. 
Thus, North Korea more clearly showed its line for communization 
of the South. He revealed that the ROK established a firm 
security posture in close cooperation with the United States, 
including 24-hour operation of the AWACS system. 
  Concerning the issue of the North Korean residents' escape 
to 
China, which was recently intensively reported by KBS, Deputy 
Prime Minister Yi said that this issue was related not only to 
the ROK and North Korea but also to China, and as a result of 
this, the exercise of the rights for diplomatic protection is 
very difficult. However, he said, the government will make 
diplomatic efforts to solve the issue at an early date. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

