<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN `Discussing' DPRK Inspections Within Month </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2603040094 Seoul SEOUL SINMUN in Korean 26 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> SK2603040094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul SEOUL SINMUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Yim Chun-ung from UN Headquarters in New York] </F>
  [Text] According to information received from a UN source 
on 25 March, while discussing the adoption of a resolution 
urging North Korea to allow additional nuclear inspections, the 
United States, Britain, France, and Russia -- permanent member 
nations of the UN Security Council -- are now considering 
demanding that North Korea allow additional inspections by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] within one month. 
  The source said: "The draft of the resolution prepared by 
friendly nations stipulates that 'the IAEA should report, within 
a month after it adopts a resolution on North Korea, if North 
Korea observes the Nuclear Safeguards Accord.'" It added: 
"This means North Korea is urged to allow additional 
inspections within one month." 
  The source also said: "If the UN Security Council decides to 
adopt this draft, North Korea must have consultations with the 
IAEA on the additional inspections within this period." 
  Prior to this, IAEA Director-General Hans Blix attended the 
UN Security Council meeting held on 25 March and said: "In 
order to maintain the continuity of nuclear inspections of North 
Korea, an IAEA inspection team has to enter North Korea again in 
six weeks to replace batteries and film." 

</TEXT>

