<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   South's Military Power Said Superior to North </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2803033294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0301 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2803033294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 28 (YONHAP) -- Defense Minister Yi 
Pyong- tae said Monday that South Korean military power is 
superior to that of the North. 
  Yi wrote in the KUKJONG SINMUM, an administration newspaper 
for public servants: "The combat ability as well as performance 
of equipment of the South Korean military are superior to those 
of the North Korean military. And our scientific war 
performance system overwhelms the North Korean one. 
  "Even if North Korea misjudges the situation and provokes a 
full- fledged war, it will taste only miserable defeat. The 
joint South Korean and U.S. forces will win a decisive victory 
after all." 
  The government's overall policy, however, is to deter North 
Korea's development of nuclear weaponry while preventing war and 
solving the nuclear problem peacefully, although security on the 
Korean peninsula is subject to increasing tension. 
  "For the survival of the nation, we must keep the North from 
developing nuclear weapons. Moreover, the military should adopt 
a perfect defense posture to immediately meet any situation that 
might arise if the North Korean nuclear problem is not solved in 
a peaceful way." 
  On a promising note, he said the military has not found any 
signs of an imminent North Korean attack on the South. 
  "The reason why the North is threatening the South is that 
it 
wants to control the North Korean people, who are agitated over 
the economic crisis. The North is also trying to obtain the 
maximum concessions from the United States and disturb the South 
psychologically." 
  Yi added that the South Korean military has prepared a 
water- 
tight defense posture. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

