<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Inter-Korean Trade Continues After Talks Break </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2803011694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0051 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2803011694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 28 (YONHAP) -- Inter-Korean trade is 
taking root despite the heightened tension caused by the North 
Korean nuclear problem, the Korea Foreign Trade Association 
(KFTA) said Monday. 
  The realization ratio of inter-Korean trade -- the ratio of 
the amount of trade actually realized to the amount the 
government approved in advance -- reached an all-time high of 
93.9 percent last year, according to the KFTA. 
  The ratio was only 53.7 percent and 57.9 percent in 1990 and 
1991, respectively, before soaring to 81.2 percent in 1992. 
  A KFTA official said, "you can say the period between 1989 
and 1992 was a mock-up stage for inter-Korean trade, but from 
last year the trade entered into a stable period." 
  An official at Samsung Co., which recorded the most trade 
with the North last year, said, "South Korean investment in the 
North was put off after the inter-Korean working-level contact 
ruptured. But trade is still going on." 

</TEXT>

