<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Departs To Hold Talks in U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2603032594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0250 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2603032594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 26 (YONHAP) -- Foreign Minister Han 
Sung- chu is headed for the United States via Beijing for 
strategically important talks on the North Korean nuclear issue 
with Washington and the United Nations, the Foreign Ministry 
said Saturday. 
  Han goes to Beijing on Sunday to join President Kim 
Yong-sam, 
who is continuing his state tour of Japan and China, the foreign 
minister embarks on a separate trip to Washington, D.C., on 
March 29 and will shuttle back and forth between the United 
Nations until April 2 to negotiate the contents of the Security 
Council resolution on North Korea. 
  While in the U.S. capital, Han is expected to meet Secretary 
of State Warren Christopher and possibly Defense Secretary 
William Perry. 
  At the United Nations, he will confer with Security Council 
President Jean-Bernard Merimee. 
  The foreign minister stops off in Tokyo on his way home from 
April 2-4 for talks with his Japanese counterpart Tsutomu Hata 
and Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  The Security Council is ready to adopt a resolution on the 
North Korean nuclear issue sometime next week, when it will 
likely demand immediate inspections by the International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA). 
  Han has timed his visit to New York to coordinate with 
Security Council members on how the United Nations should deal 
with the nuclear problem. 
  In Washington, the foreign minister will need to discuss the 
fate of the South Korea-U.S. joint military exercise "Team 
Spirit," specifically whether and when to hold it this year. 
  South Korea and the United States, although they have 
recently taken a hard-line stance outwardly, are expected to 
discuss possible ways to bring North Korea back to the 
negotiating table. 

</TEXT>

