<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plan To Deploy U.S. Fighter Jets Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2703093994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0922 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2703093994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["U.S. Prepearing Immediate Air Force Deployment in Case of </F>
War"--YONHAP headline] 
txt}[Text] New York, March 26 (YONHAP) -- The United States is 
planning instantaneous deployment of ultra-modern fighter jets 
to South Korea and Japan in case of North Korean aggression, THE 
NEW YORK TIMES reported in its Sunday edition. 
  Secretary of Defense William Perry handed down instructions 
that include sending tactical aircrafts to South Korea within a 
day or two at outbreak of war, and the U.S. Air Force in Korea 
was ordered to increase its artillery and other supplies as 
backup, the paper said. 
  Only one of the three U.S. Air Force battalions stationed in 
Korea, comprised of 24 F-16s, can carry laser-guided bombs, 
according to the paper. 
  The U.S. decision to be prepared for armed conflict on the 
Korean peninsula was based on South Korea's physical distance 
from the United States and lacking scale of the U.S. forces 
there, it said. 
  Perry was quoted as saying that the United States will watch 
for another four to six weeks whether North Korea will allow 
international nuclear inspections before pushing for economic 
sanctions. 
  The paper went on to say China opposes a U.N. Security 
Council resolution, recommending instead a statement issued by 
the council president. 
  Washington could agree to the idea if the statement clearly 
indicates possibility of sanctions if North Korea ignores the 
warning about inspection demands, the paper said. 

</TEXT>

