<DATE1>  28 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Ministry To Probe Yulgok Force Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2803033094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0242 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2803033094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 28 (YONHAP) -- The Defense Ministry's 
Armed Forces special inspection group, starting early next 
month, will examine large-scale construction projects being 
carried out under the force improvement plan codenamed Yulgok. 
  The inspection, in line with a government-wide move to stamp 
out irregularities related to state-funded construction 
projects, will focus on how Yulgok projects were awarded to 
civilian contractors, whether they are proceeding as scheduled 
and if there are any irregularities, ministry officials said 
Monday. 
  Most of these projects were launched as long-term 
undertakings under a tight security lid and thus have not been 
inspected over the years. 
  The first-time inspection will be extensive in covering many 
Yulgok construction projects and put particular stress on 
checking whether project officials have taken bribes, an 
official said. 

</TEXT>

